acceptOwnership().details: The new owner accepts the ownership transfer.

addContract(string,string,uint256,uint25.details: CAREFUL - WARNING: Choose the value for maintMarginFracHdths carefully. It can not be                         lowered after adding the contract because that would result in                         liquidations.IMPORTANT: The added contract starts out in paused state and requires that a Chainlink                 Datastreams Feed ID be configured along with an initial oracle price set before                 unpausing is possible (unless the perpetual is configured to ignore the oracle                 price with a call to Owner::setIgnOracle).                 Unpausing the first time determines the initial funding event block.                 Prior to unpausing the first time, it is advisable to ensure that the default                 values of the following settings are desired:                   * Liquidation proceed split parameters:                     - liqInsAmtPer100K                     - liqUserAmtPer100K                   * Fee split parameter:                     - insAmtPer100K                   * Open interest limiting parameters:                     - unityDescentThreshHdths                     - overColDescentThreshHdths                     - maxOpenInterestLNS                   * Oracle tolerance and age parameters:                     - indexOracleTolPer100k                     - refPriceMaxAgeSec                   * Funding rate parameters:                     - absFundingClampPctPer100K

params.basePricePNS: CAREFUL! This is the base price for prices in the perpetual contract's                     order book. The order book is able to represent 2^24-1 price levels. The                     base price determines the minimum price the order book can represent in                     Price Number System (PNS).                     For example, if the PNS for the perpetual is configured with 2 decimals and                     the lowest price the order book can represent is desired to be $1000.01,                     then basePricePNS should be set to 1_000_00, the last two digits accounting                     for the two decimal places, the value being .01 less because the price                     levels DO NOT INCLUDE the basePricePNS.
params.initMarginFracHdths: is the Initial Margin Fraction (IMF) in hundredths. It is                            constrained to the range [1, 10,000], which corresponds to an IMF                            range of [1/100, 100.00]. IMF is synonymous with the leverage of a                            position. This value determines the maximum initial leverage a                            position may be opened with. This value is derated towards unity and                            eventually 1/100th as open interest of the perpetual contract                            increases towards the maximum open interest.
params.lotDecimals: CAREFUL! This is the number of decimals to use for the perpetual contract's                    position lot size, the Lot Number System (LNS). LNS is limited to 40-bits                    and the maximum lot size of a position is thus 40^2 - 1, divided by                    10^lotDecimals. This directly effects the maximum notional open interest                    possible for the perpetual contract as well as the minimum amount that can                    be traded (ignoring the minimum post and settle amounts). This value is                    constrained to the absolute range [0,6], but jointly constrained with the                    priceDecimals value to sum to 6 or less, both values being greater than or                    equal to zero.
params.maintMarginFracHdths: is the Maintenance Margin Fraction (MMF) in hundredths. It is                             constrained to the range [1, 10,000], which corresponds to an MMF                             range of [1/100, 100.00]. The MMF determines when a position can be                             liquidated and is used to compute the value a position must exceed                             to avoid liquidation. It must exceed initMarginFracHdths.                             IMPORTANT: See dev note warning below about maintMarginFracHdths.
params.makerFeePer100K: is the maker fee in hundred-thousandths. It is constrained to the                        absolute range [0, _MAX_FEE].
params.name: is the name of the perpetual contract, limited to _MAX_NAME_BYTES.
params.perpId: is the unique id for this perpetual contract. Cannot already be in use; previous               contract must be properly unwound and deleted from the exchange before               re-assigning. Valid values in the range [0,_MAX_CONTRACT_ID].
params.priceDecimals: CAREFUL! This is the number of decimals to use for the order book's Price                      Number System (PNS). It directly determines the range of prices that the                      order book can operate and the minimum spread. It is constrained to the                      absolute range [0,6], but jointly constrained with the lotDecimals value                      to sum to 6 or less, both values being greater than or equal to zero.                      For example, there are only 2^24 - 2 price levels, ~16M. If two price                      decimals are specified and the basePricePNS is zero, then the approximate                      price range of the order book would be [$0.01, $((2^24 - 2)/100)] The                      spread resolution would be in increments of $0.01. The perpetual would not                      be able to trade at prices above $((2^24 - 2)/100).
params.symbol: is the symbol for the perpetual contract, limited to _MAX_SYMBOL_BYTES.
params.takerFeePer100K: is the taker fee in hundred-thousandths. It is constrained to the                        absolute range [0, _MAX_FEE].

params.signatures: is an array of OrderSignature instances, which uniquely describe an                   order to be cancelled by describing the perpetual contract id and order id                   for the order.

params.allow: is a boolean that if true, indicates that the exchange account, if it exists,              corresponding to the address in msg.sender, wishes to enable order forwarding. If              false, the ability for the Administration role to forward orders for this account              is disabled.

autoDeleverage((uint256,uint256,uint256[.details: IMPORTANT: No check is made on the sorting of sortedPositionIds provided in each                 auto-deleverage description struct. Positions specified therein should have                 positive value, otherwise they are skipped and result in wasted gas use.

params.adlDescs: is an array of auto-deleverage description structs, providing the necessary                 incredients to deleverage a batch of positions in one or more perpetual                 contracts. See the documentation for struct OperationStructs::AdlDesc for more                 information.
params.revertOnFail: reverts on error conditions when true, attempts to emit log events when                     false.

params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual to clear unwind initialization state on.

params.amountCNS: is the amount of collateral token deposited from the user's wallet to the                  exchange on account creation. Must exceed _minAccountOpenCNS.

returns.accountId: is the unique account id corresponding to the address msg.sender on the                   exchange.

params.amountCNS: is the amount of collateral token to deposit.
is the amount of collateral token to transfer to the protocol balance.

params.forwardedOrders: is an array of FwdOrderDesc instances describing the account, fee        override and order description for each order being forwarded. See the documentation for        the structs FwdOrderDesc and OrderDesc for more information.

execFznAccountPosOps((uint256,(uint256,u.details: IMPORTANT: Constraints on orders placed by this function are outlined below.

params.fznAccountCloseOrders: is an array of FznOrderDesc instances describing the account, fee        override and order description for each order being forwarded. See the documentation for        the structs FznOrderDesc and OrderDesc for more information.

execOpsAndOrders((uint256,uint256,uint8,.details: IMPORTANT: Note that operation descriptions, operations, are executed before order                 descriptions, orderDescs.                 This method is expected to fail if invalid perpetual contract ids are                 specified or if the calling account is frozen.

params.operations: is an array of operation descriptions to be executed in order (lowest array                   index first). See the documentation for the struct OpDesc for details.
params.orderDescs: is an array of order descriptions to be executed in order (lowest array index                   first). See the documentation for the struct OrderDesc for details.
params.revertOnFail: if set to true will revert for any errors encountered while executing                     operation and order descriptions. If false, recoverable errors will have a                     log message emitted instead of reverting and causing the entire batch of                     operations and orders to fail.

returns.signatures: is an array of structs containing unique identification of any orders posted                    to a perpetual's order book as a result of executing the corresponding order                    description. If orderDescs 0, 3 and 9 in a 10 order description array result                    in orders being posted to the perpetual's order book, then signatures 0, 3,                    and 9 would expected to have non zero struct fields, identifiying each                    order. The length of the signatures array returned should match the length                    of the provide orderDescs array.

execOrder((uint256,uint256,uint8,uint256.details: This method is expected to fail if the specified account is frozen or an invalid perpetual      contract id is specified. Furthermore, unlike the execOpsAndOrders command where it's      possible to have events emitted on failure instead of reverting, this method will revert      wherever possible.

params.orderDesc: is an order description, detailing the order requested by the account. See the                  documentation for struct OrderDesc for details.

returns.signature: is a struct containing unique identification of an order, if posted to a                   perpetual's order book as a result of the order description. If no order is                   posted to the book, the struct's values are zero.

params.operations: is an array of OpDesc structs, describing operations to perform on various                   perpetual contracts. Incorrect perp ids in the OpDesc structs will result in                   reverting, otherwise operations are attempt with error conditions emitted as                   event logs where possible.

forceClose(uint256,uint256,uint256[],boo.details: IMPORTANT: No check is made on the sorting of sortedPositionIds. Positions specified therein                 should have positive value, otherwise they are skipped and result in wasted gas                 use.IMPORTANT: Force close criteria are managed by supporting infrastructure. For instance, a                 request to force close of a position from a user to the position administator,                 requires a check to ensure that book inventory is sufficiently lacking. No such                 checks are made herein.

params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract on which to perform the force close.
params.posAccountId: is the unique id of the account with a position to deleverage in the                     specified perpetual contract.
params.revertOnFail: reverts on error conditions when true, attempts to emit log events when                     false.
params.sortedPositionIds: is a list of positions within the specified perpetual contract that are                          the opposite position type of the position held by posAccountId                          (i.e. if posAccountId holds a long position, the positions of ids                          in this list should be short positions). The sort order may be                          adjusted, but the canonical best practice is to sort first by highest                          profit and loss and then by highest leverage.

returns.success: is a boolean value that when true, indices that the force close was                 successfully completed.

params.perpId: the id of the perp to fetch orders from.
params.priceONS: a price in Orderbook Number System (ONS) to use as the basis to find the                 next lower price containing orders. If a value greater than MAX_ONS is                 specified, the functionr reverts with an error.

returns.priceBelowONS: is the next lower price in the order book containing orders. If there                       are no orders below the specified price, priceONS, then UNDEF_PRICE_ONS                       is returned.

getOrderIdIndex(uint256).details: See Index16Bit.sol for more information on the structure of the root and leaf nodes.

params.perpId: is the id of the perp to fetch the order id data from.

returns.leaves: is an ordered array of 256-bit containers that represent the leaves of the                16-bit order id index.                The Least-Significant Bit (LSB) of the first element of the array is order id                zero, which is reserved as _NULL_ORDER_ID. It is not used for orders.                The second bit of the first element of the array is order id 1 and so forth.                Except for order id zero, if the value of a bit is one, it indicates that the                order id is in use for an existing order. If the value of the bit is zero, it                indicates the order id is not currently in use. For order id zero, the bit will                be one to indicate the reserved status.                The LSB of the second element of the array is order id 256, the LSB of the third                element of the array is order id 512, and so so forth up to the last possible                order id, which is the Most-Significant Bit (MSB) of the last element of the                array, order id 65535.
returns.numOrders: is the number of order ids currently in use in the returned order id index                   leaves.
returns.root: is a 256-bit container with each bit corresponding to a leaf in the leaves. The              Least-Significant Bit (LSB) corresponds to the first leaves element, and so forth.              If a bit is zero it indicates that all ids in the corresponding leaf node are in              use. If the bit is one, it indicates that one or more numbers in the corresponding              leaf node is NOT in use.

getOrdersAtPriceLevel(uint256,uint256,ui.details: to paginate, start with pageStartOrderId at NULL_ORDER_ID. Then if the resulting      ordersAtPriceLevel is full of valid orders, pass the nextOrderId value of the last node      to this method on a subsequent call and repeat until the orders at price level does not      contain a full list of valid orders.

params.ordersPerPage: is the number of orders to return per page of orders. If set to 0, the                      maximum number of orders, _MAX_ORDERS_PER_PAGE, is returned.
params.pageStartOrderId: is the first order at price level priceONS to start fetching from. If                         this value is NULL_ORDER_ID, the function starts at the first order at                         at the price level, if it exists (otherwise it returns an empty list).                         If the value specified is at a different price level than priceONS                         specified, the transaction reverts with an error.
params.perpId: the id of the perp to fetch orders from.
params.priceONS: the price in Orderbook Number System (ONS) to fetch orders from. If the price                 specified is UNDEF_PRICE_ONS, the function returns an empty list.

returns.numOrders: is the number of valid orders returned in the array of Order structs,         ordersAtPriceLevel.
returns.ordersAtPriceLevel: is an array of Order structs of the orders in FIFO order at the                            specified price level. Note that if the number of orders that exist                            is less than the number of ordersPerPage, a list of length                            ordersPerPage is still returned, but only orders with lotLNS > 0                            are valid. Orders with lotLNS == 0 are just empty array values.

getPositions(uint256,uint256,uint256).details: to paginate, start withthe pageStartPositionId at NULL_ACCOUNT_ID. Then if the resulting      positions is full of valid positions, pass the nextNodeId of the value of the last      element to this function on a subsequent call and repeat until the positions array does      not contain a full list of valid positions.

params.pageStartPositionId: is the first position in the perpetual contract to start fetching        from. If this value is NULL_ACCOUNT_ID, the function starts at the first position, if        it exists otherwise it returns an empty list).
params.perpId: the id of the perp to fetch orders from.
params.positionsPerPage: is the number of positions to return per page. If set to 0, the                         maximum number of positions, _MAX_POSITIONS_PER_PAGE, is returned.

returns.numPositions: is the number of valid positions returned in the array of PositionInfo                      structs, positions.
returns.positions: is an array of PositionInfo structs in the perpetual contract, in First In                   First Out (FIFO) order (i.e. starting with the position that was last                   modified earliest in time). Note that if the number of positions that exist                   is less than the number of positionsPerPage, a list of length                   positionsPerPage is still returned but only positions with lotLNS > 0 are                   valid. Positions with lotLNS == 0 are empty array values.

params.unwindInitPosBalCNS: is the initial perpetual contract position balance at the start of                           the unwind process. (The insurance funds are transferred to this                           balance before it is set in state).
params.unwindStarted: is a boolean that if true, indicates the unwind process has started.
params.unwindSumPositiveFmvCNS: is the sum of positive Fair Market Value (FMV) of all positions                               at the start of the unwind process, set by backend                               infrastructure in Owner::initUnwindContract.

increasePositionCollateral(uint256,uint2.details: The position collateral (depositCNS) is currently limited to 80-bits. Also note that CNS      values are C._COLLAT_DEC decimal places. This function will fail if the total collateral      of the position exceeds the aforementioned limit.      This method is expected to fail if an invalid perpetual contract id is specified or if the      calling account is frozen.

params.amountCNS: is the amount of collateral to add to the position. Must be greater than                  zero. See dev note below.
params.perpId: is the perpetual contract id of the perpetual containing the account's position,               to add collateral to.

initUnwindContract(uint256,uint256).details: IMPORTANT - CAREFUL:          If this is called to initialize state and it is then decided to adjust the index price          before starting unwind, the sumPositiveFmvCNS must be re-calculated at the perpetual's          new index price. The re-calculated price then needs to be passed into this method          before starting the unwind process. Otherwise the pro-rata payments will be incorrect          as they be using an incorrect denominator. (To call this method a second time,          unwindContract must not have been called yet and clearInitUnwindContract must be          called.)          UNDER NO CIRCUMSTANCES SHOULD THE INDEX PRICE BE CHANGED AFTER CALLING THIS METHOD          WITHOUT SUBSEQUENTLY CALLING THIS METHOD WITH AN UPDATED VALUE FOR sumPositiveFmvCNS.

params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual to unwind.
params.sumPositiveFmvCNS: is the sum of the Fair Market Value (FMV) of each position in the                          perepetual contract at the recorded index price, where each FMV is                          positive, at the time the first unwind operation is started.

params.liquidationDesc: is a LiquidationDesc instance that describes the position to                        be liquidated and parameters controlling the liquidation. See the                        LiquidationDesc struct documentation for more details.

params.liquidationDescs: is an array of LiquidationDesc instances describing positions to                         be liquidated and parameters controlling each liquidation.
params.revertOnFail: reverts on error conditions when true, attempts to emit log events when                     false.

owner().details: Returns the address of the current owner.

params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to pause.

pendingOwner().details: Returns the address of the pending owner.

removeContract(uint256).details: CAREFUL: In order to remove a contract:                 * It's open interest must be zero (this can be accomplished if there are still                   positions by calling the unwind function).                 * It must be in paused state.               Ideally:                 * All orders should be removed after the perpetual is unwound using the                   adminCancelOrders function--though it is preferrable that users cancel their                   own orders so that order recycling fees are remitted to them.

params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to remove.

renounceOwnership().details: Leaves the contract without owner. It will not be possible to call `onlyOwner` functions. Can only be called by the current owner. NOTE: Renouncing ownership will leave the contract without an owner, thereby disabling any functionality that is only available to the owner.

params.add: is a boolean value that when true, gives the address specified  administrator            priviledges. When false, this call removes those priviledges from the specified            address.
params.administrator: is the address to add or remove administator priviledges from.

setContractPaused(uint256,bool).details: IMPORTANT: The perpetual contract after being added is configured to be paused. It cannot                 be initially unpaused until the following is true if the perpetual is not                 ignoring oracle prices (see Owner::setIgnOracle):                   1. The Chainlink Datastreams Oracle verify proxy is set for the exchange                      (State::_iLinkVerifierProxy).                   2. The Chainlink Datastreams Oracle feed id for the perpetual contract is set                      (Perpetual::linkFeedId).                   3. The oracle price for the perpetual contract has been successfully set at                      least once from a Chainlink Datastreams Oracle price report.                 If the perpetual is ignoring oracle prices, then the index price must be set                 before unpausing is allowed.IMPORTANT: The perpetual contract cannot be unpaused if the unwind process has been                 initialized.

params.paused: pauses the perpetual contract when true, unpauses it when false.
params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to pause.

params.halted: when true halts the exchange, when false, un-halts the exchange.

params.insAmtPer100K: is the split in hudred-thousandths directed to the insurance fund from the                      total fee collected. Acceptable values range from [0, _DENOMINATOR_100K].                      Setting this value implicitly sets the amount directed to the protocol                      balance because it is the remaining amount from the total fee collected.
params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to set the fee parameters on.

setFreezeStatus(address,uint8).details: Differs from Admin::setFrozen because this function can un-freeze an account.

params.account: is the address of the account to set the frozen status of.
params.status: is the frozen status to set the account to.

setFrozen(address,uint8).details: Differs from owner::setFreezeStatus because this function cannot un-freeze an account.

params.account: is the address of the account to set the frozen status of.
params.status: is the frozen status to set the account to.

params.absFundingClampPctPer100K: is the funding clamp percentage in hundred-thousandths. The                                  acceptable range is [0, _ABS_MAX_FR_CLAMP_PCT_100K].
params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to set the funding clamp percent on.

setFundingSum(uint256,int256,uint32,bool.details: IMPORTANT: This function must be called within C._APRX_ONE_MIN_MON_BLKS prior to the next                 funding event block and the funding event block to be successful.                 The funding sum must be unset already or allowOverwrite should be set to true.                 If the perpetual is not configured to ingore oracle prices, then the                 indexPricePNS value:                   - should be within the perpetual contract's constrained PNS range.                   - should be within the perpetual tolerance property, indexOracleTolPer100k,                     of the current oracle price.                 Also, if not ignoring oracle prices, then oracle price must be less than                 Perpetual::refPriceMaxAgeSec old.

params.allowOverwrite: when true, allows a funding sum value to be overwritten, when false                       will revert if the funding sum value is already set. Only applies to                       funding events that occur immediately in the future and within the                       funding rate window prior to the future funding event block, see                       immutable FundingRate::_MAX_WINDOW_TO_SET_FUNDING (which is                       C._APRX_ONE_MIN_MON_BLKS unless contract is being tested).
params.fundingRatePct100k: is the funding rate in 1/100,000ths. If the value specified exceeds        the perpetual maximum funding rate property, absFundingClampPctPer100K, then the funding        rate will clamp to that value.
params.indexPricePNS: is the index price applicable to the specified funding rate (this value is                      multiplied by the funding rate to obtain the funding payment per lot).                      The funding payment per lot is then added to the previous sum of all                      preceding funding payments per lot, hence the method being called                      "setFundingSum".
params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to set the funding sum of.
params.revertOnFail: when true, causes any errors to revert. When false, the function will emit                     a log event for any error encountered and return.

setIgnOracle(uint256,bool).details: IMPORTANT: Setting a perpetual contract to NOT ignore oracle pricing if it is currently                 ignoring oracle pricing requires the following:                     1. The Chainlink Datastreams Oracle verify proxy is set for the exchange                        (State::_iLinkVerifierProxy).                     2. The Chainlink Datastreams Oracle feed id for the perpetual contract is                        set (Perpetual::linkFeedId).

params.ignOracle: is a boolean value that if true, isntructs the perpetual contract to ignore                  oracle price checks as detailed above in the notice documentation.
params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to set whether or not to ignore               oracle prices.

params.maxAgeSec: is the maximum age in seconds. The Acceptable range is                  [0, _MAX_REF_PRICE_AGE]
params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to set the maximum oragle age on.
is the unique id of the perpetual contract to configure the index-oracle price               tolerance on.
params.tolerancePer100k: is the permitted tolerance between the index price and oracle price                         values, specified in hundred-thousandths. The Acceptable range is                         [0, _MAX_INDEX_ORACLE_TOL].

setInitialMarginFraction(uint256,uint256.details: IMPORTANT: This value is derated as the open interest proceeds towards the perpetual                 contract's maximum open interest. See CalculationsLib::getCurrentIMF for more                 information.

params.initMarginFracHdths: is the IMF in hundredths. Acceptable range is from [1, 10,000] which                            represents IMF or initial leverage from [1/100, 100.0]. However,                            this value is further constrained to be greater than the Maintenance                            Margin Fraction (MMF)--trying to set it lower will revert.
params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to set the IMF on.

params.verifierProxy: the address of the Chainlink Datastreams Verifier Proxy.

setLiquidationParams(uint256,uint256,uin.details: IMPORTANT: The amount in hundred-thousandths is implicitly set as the difference between                 _DENOMINATOR_100K and the sum of the insAmtPer100K and userAmtPer100K.

params.insAmtPer100K: is the portion of fees to direct to the perpetual contract's insurance                      balance in hundred-thousandths. Acceptable values range from                      [0, _DENOMINATOR_100K]. However, the sum of this value and userAmtPer100K                      are jointly constrained to be less than or equal to _DENOMINATOR_100K.
params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to set the liquidation parameters of.
params.userAmtPer100K: is the portion of fees to direct to the original position holder's                       account balance, in hundred-thousandths. Acceptable values range from                       [0, DENOMINATOR_100K]. However, the sum of this value and insAmtPer100K                       are jointly constrained to be less than or equal to _DENOMINATOR_100K.

params.maintMarginFracHdths: is the MMF in hundredths. Acceptable range is from [1, 10,000] which                              represents MMF from [1/100, 100.0]. However, this value is further                              constrained by itself and the IMF. This value cannot be less than                              the IMF and this value cannot be less than its current value.                              Reducing the existing value changes the system such that existing                              positions are subject to liquidation, despite the previous MMF                              potentially allowing them to avoid liquidation.
params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to set the MMF on.

params.makerFeePer100K: is the maker fee expressed in hundred-thousandths (basis point tenths).                        Acceptable values range from [0, _MAX_FEE].
params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to set the maker fee on.

setMaxOpenInterest(uint256,uint256).details: CAREFUL: Be very careful setting this value to a lower amount than the current               value--doing so can have profound effects on liquidity and the ability for users               to exit positions on the order book.

params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual to set the maximum open interest on.

params.amountCNS: is the minimum amount required to open an account. Allowable values are in the                  following range: [0,_MAX_ACCT_OPEN_CNS].

setMinPost(uint256).details: IMPORTANT: For gas reduction, the lowest 4-decimals of value minPostCNS are truncated                 away, so setting them has no effect.For information about the minimum post scenarios and how this value affects them, consult      the dev note for Checks::lessThanMinimumOrder which explains this with a table.

params.minPostCNS: is the minimum post amount in collateral tokens. Acceptable values are in the                    range [0, 163830000], representing [$0.00, $163.83]. See important dev note                    below about this value's treatment in the system.

setMinSettle(uint256).details: IMPORTANT: For gas reduction, the lowest 4-decimals of value minSettleCNS are truncated                 away, so setting them has no effect.For information about the minimum post scenarios and how this value affects them, consult      the dev note for Checks::lessThanMinimumOrder which explains this with a table.

params.minSettleCNS: is the minimum settle amount in collateral tokens. Acceptable values are                     in the range [0, 163830000], representing [$0.00, $163.83]. See important                     dev note below about this value's treatment in the system.

setOverCollatDescentThreshold(uint256,ui.details: CAREFUL: Be careful setting this value to a lower amount than the current value--doing so               can have profound effects on liquidity and the ability for users to exit               positions on the order book.

params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to set the over collateral descent               threshold on.
params.threshHdths: is the threshold in hundredths of the perpetual contract's maximum open                    intererest, wherein the descent to 1/100th IMF begins. Valid range of values                    is [_MIN_DESCENT_THRESH_HDTHS, _MAX_DESCENT_THRESH_HDTHS]. However the value                    configured must also be greater than the unity descent threshold                    (unityDescentThreshHdths).

params.permCancelMinOrders: is the minimum number of orders that must be present on the order                            book before permissioned cancellation is possible. Valid range is                            [_MIN_PERM_CANCEL_ORDERS, _MAX_ORDERS].
params.permCancelSegment: is the segment of the orders between the maximum ask price and minimum                          ask price or the minimum bid price and maximum bid price where orders                          may be cancelled if permissioned cancellation is possible. The valid                          range of this value is [2, 9].                          For example, if the value 2 is specified, then the segment is the                          upper half of the ask orders or lower half of the bid orders, which                          may be cancelled. If the value 9 is specified, then the segment of                          orders which may be cancelled is the upper 1/9th of the ask orders or                          the lower 1/9th of the bid orders.
params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to set the permissioned cancel               parameters on.

setPerpLinkDsFeedId(uint256,bytes32).details: Requires the perpetual contract is paused.

params.feedId: the Chainlink Datastreams Oracle corresponding to the underlying asset of the               perpetual contract given by perpId.
params.perpId: is the id of the perpetual contract to set the Chainlink Datastreams Oracle feed               id on.

params.add: is a boolean value that when true, gives the address specified in priceAdministrator            price administrator priviledges. When false, this call removes those priviledges            from the specified address.
params.priceAdministrator: is the address to add or remove price administator priviledges from.

setRecycleFee(uint256).details: IMPORTANT: For gas reduction, the lowest 4-decimals of value recycleFeeCNS are truncated                 away, so setting them has no effect.

params.recycleFeeCNS: is the recycle fee. Acceptable values are in the range [0, 163830000],                      representing [$0.00, $163.83]. See important dev note below about this                      value's treatment in the system.

params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to set the taker fee on.
params.takerFeePer100K: is the taker fee expressed in hundred-thousandths (basis point tenths).                        Acceptable values range from [0, _MAX_FEE].

params.thousandthsTvl: is the thousandths of Total Value Locked (TVL), in the range [1,2500]                       (effectively 0.001 to 0.25 of TVL), that can be withdrawn per withdraw                       rate limit period. The specified thousandthsTvl of the TVL is allowed to                       be withdrawn through approximately an hour, with a burst of 1/4 the                       amount in approximately the first fifteen minutes of the withdrawal rate                       limit period with the remainder being freed per withdrawal at the rate                       per block, each block.                       If the specified thousandthsTvl results in an amount less than                       _MIN_WITHDRAW_LIMIT_CNS permitted for the withdraw rate limit period,                       then _MIN_WITHDRAW_LIMIT_CNS is permitted instead.

setUnityDescentThreshold(uint256,uint256.details: CAREFUL: Be very careful setting this value to a lower amount than the current               value--doing so can have profound effects on liquidity and the ability for users               to exit positions on the order book.

params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to set the unity descent threshold on.
params.threshHdths: is the threshold in hundredths of the perpetual contract's maximum open                    intererest, wherein the descent to unity IMF begins. Valid range of values                    is [_MIN_DESCENT_THRESH_HDTHS, _MAX_DESCENT_THRESH_HDTHS]. However the value                    configured must also be less than the over collateral descent threshold                    (overColDescentThreshHdths).

transferOwnership(address).details: Starts the ownership transfer of the contract to a new account. Replaces the pending transfer if there is one. Can only be called by the current owner.

unwindContract(uint256,uint256,bool).details: The unwind process is as follows:     1. The perpetual contract is paused.     2. Backend infrastructure assesses the recorded index price in the perpetual contract,        potentially updating it through a governance process that may involve decoupling from        the price oracle.     3. Backend infrastructure computes the sum of the Fair Market Value (FMV) at the recorded        index price for all positions where FMV > 0.     4. Backend infrastructure adjusts the perpetual contract's insurance balance, if necessary,        with an internal transfer (either to or from the perpetual contract's insurance balance).     5. Backend infrastructure calls function Owner::initUnwindContract to set the initial        perpetual state for the unwind process.     7. Backend infrastructure calls Owner::unwindContract repeatedly until all positions are cleared.IMPORTANT - CAREFUL: Cannot unpause the contract once this process has started, until it                           is complete.IMPORTANT - CAREFUL: Cannot update the contract index price once this process has                           started, until it is complete.IMPORTANT: If the perpetual insurance and position balance are zero at the start of this                 process, positions will be unwound without payment. This is not handled                 through the "allowWithoutPayment" parameter and does not emit                 PositionUnwoundWithoutPayment events. However, it is possible in this                 situation to see the position's FMV at unwind in the PositionUnwound event and                 for the protocol to consider compensation through an internal transfer at a                 later time.

params.allowWithoutPayment: is a boolean that when true, instructs the function to unwind                            positions, clearing them from the perpetual, even if the calculated                            payment to the position holder cannot be paid. A                            PositionUnwoundWithoutPayment event is emitted that contains the                            unpaied amount. This allows clearing of state if the perpetual is                            insolvent.
params.maxPosToUnwind: is the maximum number of positions to unwind per call to unwind. If set                       to zero then this function will initialize the unwind balance and mark                       the unwind process as having started. See dev notes below for                       implications. CAREFUL!
params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual to unwind.

updateIndexPricePNS(uint256,uint256).details: IMPORTANT: The index price, indexPricePNS, proposed must be within the PNS number range                 for the corresponding perpetual contract. If the perpetual is configured to                 not ignore oracle prices, then the index price must be within the perpetual                 tolerance property, indexOracleTolPer100k, of the current oracle price. The                 oracle price must be less than the perpetual property, refPriceMaxAgeSec, old.IMPORTANT: The index price cannot be updated if the unwind process has been started.

params.indexPricePNS: is the value to set the perpetual contract's index price to.
params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to update the index price of.

updateOraclePrice(uint256,bytes).details: This will fail if the price report is older than the last update. (see Perpetual struct      member linkTimestamp).      IMPORTANT: The resolution of a Monad block is 0.5 seconds. The resolution of a Chainlink                 Datastreams V3 price report is 1 second. Thus it is possible to update the                 price in one block but not possible to update it with a newer price in the                 second block if both price reports share the same timestamp.

params.perpId: is the perpetual contract id of the perpetual to update the oracle price on.
params.unverifiedReport: is an unverified, signed Chainlink Datastreams V3 price report for the        feed id for this perpetual (see Perpetual struct member linkFeedId).

withdrawCollateral(uint256).details: IMPORTANT: Available collateral differs from the account's collateral token balance. It is                 the difference between the account's collateral token balance and locked token                 balance. The locked balance can be freed by cancelling any existing open long                 or open short orders.                 To determine the collateral token account balance, locked balance, and order                 lock information, consult the following functions:                     * Information::getAccountId                     * Information::getAccountByAddr                     * Information::getOrderLocks                     * Information::getPerpOrderLocksIMPORTANT: The ability to withdraw funds is rate-limited across the exchange to protect                 users in the event of an attack. The rate-limit is a percentage of the TVL over                 approximately an hour. See Information::getWithdrawAllowanceData

params.amountCNS: is the amount of available collateral tokens to withdraw.

withdrawFromProtocol(uint256).details: IMPORTANT: Amount withdrawn is subject to the Withdraw Rate Limiting System (WRLS)                 constraints.

params.amountCNS: is the amount of collateral token to be withdrawn from the protocol balance.
is the amount to transfer from the user account's available balance to the                  protocol balance.

params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to transfer insurance funds to the               protocol from.

params.accountId: is the unique id of the exchange account to transfer protocol funds to.

params.insurance: is a boolean that when true, directs the funds of this transfer from the                  protocol to the specified perpetual contract's insurance fund. If false, then                  funds are directed to the specified perpetual contract's position balance.
params.perpId: is the unique id of the perpetual contract to transfer funds to.

addContract(string,string,uint256,uint25.notice: addContract adds a contract to the exchange with the specified properties.

adminCancelOrders((uint256,uint256)[]).notice: adminCancelOrders is a permissioned cancellation mechanism that allows an address with                           the Administrator role to cancel orders under the following                           conditions:                               1. The order is expired.                               2. The order book has more than OrderBook::permCancelMinOrders                                  orders and the order price is in the segment                                  OrderBook::permCancelSegment of the book defined as follows:                                                                        maxBidPrice - minBidPrice                                  - Long order:  Price < maxBidPrice - ---------------------------                                                                                 segment                                                                         maxAskPrice - minAskPrice                                  - Short order:  Price > minAskPrice + ---------------------------                                                                                  segment                                  Where segment is [2, 9].                               3. The order is on a perpetual contract where the user has just                                  been liquidated or ADL'd. (Canellation happens by the                                  liquidator or ADL mechanism automatically.)                               4. The user account is frozen, for any reason.                               5. The perpetual is paused.

allowOrderForwarding(bool).notice: allowOrderForwarding sets whether the account permits the Administrator role to forward                              exchange orders on it's behalf. This enables gas-less, click-less                              trading.

autoDeleverage((uint256,uint256,uint256[.notice: Attempts to auto-deleverage the specified positions in the provided list of         auto-deleverage description structs.

clearInitUnwindContract(uint256).notice: Clears the perpetual contract unwind process initialization state if the unwind process         has not yet started.

createAccount(uint256).notice: createAccount creates a user account on the exchange for the msg.sender address, if                       such an account doesn't already exist and sufficient collateral token is                       being deposited.

depositCollateral(uint256).notice: depositCollateral allows an existing exchange account to deposit additional exchange                           collateral tokens into their account from an external wallet. The                           exchange account id is looked up through the msg.sender address                           within the exchange's map of addresses to account ids.

depositToProtocol(uint256).notice: depositToProtocol allows the owner account to transfer collateral tokens from an                           external wallet to the protocol balance.

execFwdPositionOps((uint256,uint256,(uin.notice: execFwdPositionOps executes forwarded position operations from an address with         Administrator role priviledges on behalf of user accounts who have approved forwarding         by such a role. The forwarded operations include standard order book order types, such         as Open Long etc. as well as the ability to increase a position's collateral.

execOpsAndOrders((uint256,uint256,uint8,.notice: Executes zero or more operations and orders as specified by an account in the array of         operation descriptions, operations, and order descriptions, orderDescs. Operations are         limited to perpetual contract oracle updates. Available orders are presented in the         documentation for struct OrderDesc. Well formed operation and order descriptions will         be executed and in the event of recoverable errors, will emit error messages if         revertOnFail is false. Irrecoverable errors will result in the transaction being         reverted. The returned array, signatures, are the uniquely identifiying order         signatures corresponding to each individual order description in the event that its         execution results in a post to the perpetual contract's order book.         IMPORTANT: This will emit OracleDisabled event and continue after executing oracle                    update operations if the perpetual contract that is the target of the                    update is configured to ignore oracle prices (see Perpetual::ignOracle and                    Owner::setIgnOracle).

execOrder((uint256,uint256,uint8,uint256.notice: Executes an account's order, as described in the order description, orderDesc. If the         resulting executed order posts to a perpetual's order book, the signature value         returned uniquely identifies the order. Otherwise, a signature with all values set to         zero is returned.

execPerpOps((uint256,uint256,uint8,uint3.notice: execPerpOps executes a batch of perpetual operations as described in OpDescEnum (see                     documentation for that enum).

forceClose(uint256,uint256,uint256[],boo.notice: Force closes the position of a specified account id within a perpetual contract by         deleveraging the position against the specified, opposing, positions. The deleveraging         is performed at the current reference price.

getNextPriceBelowWithOrders(uint256,uint.notice: Gets the next price below (less than) the specified price that contains orders.

getOrderIdIndex(uint256).notice: Fetches the order id index data of the specified perpetual's order id index to allow         the caller to determine all currently used and unused order ids in the 16-bit order         space.

getOrdersAtPriceLevel(uint256,uint256,ui.notice: Gets a page of orders at the specified price level.

getPositions(uint256,uint256,uint256).notice: Gets a page of positions within the specified perpetual contract.

getUnwindInfo(uint256).notice: Gets information about a perpetual contract's unwind state.

increasePositionCollateral(uint256,uint2.notice: Increases an account's collateral in an existing position.

initUnwindContract(uint256,uint256).notice: Initializes perpetual state for performing an unwind process. Can be called to change         state as long as the unwind process has not started (indicated by         Perpetual::unwindStarted), by calling clearInitUnwindContract before calling this         function again.

liquidation((uint256,uint256,uint256,boo.notice: liquidation performs liquidation of the specified position if the value of the position                     is underneath the maintenance margin. The maintenance margin is used to                     deterimine a liquidation price for the position. If the liquidation price                     is beneath the perpetual contract's index price for a long position (or                     above it for a short position), the position can be liquidated.                     Importantly, the index price must be within a tolerance,                     Perpetual::indexOracleTolPer100k, of the perpetual contract's oracle price                     and the oracle price must be less than Perpetual::refPriceMaxAgeSec old                     (if the perpetual is not configured to ignore oracle prices, see                     Perpetual::ignOracle and Owner::setIgnOracle).                     Liquidation is performed by selling the position to the order book. If the                     fill price of this operation is at the bankruptcy price or below (when the                     margin of the position is valued at zero), then liquidation will revert (it                     must revert because matching changes state).                     The proceeds of a liquidation are divided between the original position                     holder, the protocol, and the perpetual insurance fund, according to the                     values of the following perpetual parameters:                          - Perpetual::liqProtAmtPer100K                          - Perpetual::liqInsAmtPer100K                     See the documentation of these values in the Perpetual struct.                     Optionally, the liquidation function facilitates partial liquidation,                     wherein part of a position is liquidated and the proceeds are directed to                     the remaining portion of the position as collateral to place it above the                     maintenance margin.

liquidations((uint256,uint256,uint256,bo.notice: liquidations attempts to perform a batch of operations, emitting events if possible                      when errors are encountered if revertOnFail is false. Liquidation matches                      against the book and if the resulting fill price places the liquidated                      position beneath the bankruptcy price, the liquidation must revert, which                      would then cause any batch with such a liquidation to also revert.

pauseContract(uint256).notice: pauseContract pauses the specified perpetual contract, which blocks new orders and                       position operations except for order cancellation and increasing position                       collateral.                       Importantly does not allow unpausing the contract. This must be                       performed by the Owner role.

removeContract(uint256).notice: removeContract removes a perpetual contract from the exchange.

setAdministrator(address,bool).notice: setAdministrator CAREFUL! This function allows an address to be permitted to the role                          of administrator. An administrator (not to be confused with a price                          administrator, which is a different role) can do important,                          financially impactful operations on a perpetual contract including                          pausing a contract, permissioned order cancellation, freezing of                          accounts, and order forwarding.                          This role is not suitable for a multi-sig because the frequency of                          operations and number of operations is too high. Protection against                          this role being co-opted comes in the form of the price oracle                          gaurding operations to be within acceptable tolerance, forwarding only                          to users who have granted such permission (and never to transfers on                          or off exchange from a user wallet). A last resort is the owner called                          halt function which blocks addresses with this role from acting on the                          exchange.                          The number of administrators is not limited as this role will likely                          operate with both failover and geographic redundancy.

setContractPaused(uint256,bool).notice: setContractPaused pauses or unpauses the specified perpetual contract, which blocks new                           orders and position operations except for order cancellation and                           increasing position collateral.

setExchangeHalted(bool).notice: setExchangeHalted CAREFUL! This function halts the entire exchange making all external                           functions except those restricted to the Owner role blocked from all                           users (including the Owner role).

setFeeParams(uint256,uint256).notice: setFeeParams sets the fee split between the insurance and protocol for fees collected         on maker and taker orders that open a position. (See documentation on setMakerFee and         setTakerFee).

setFreezeStatus(address,uint8).notice: setFreezeStatus sets the frozen status of an account to any of the values documented                         in FreezeStatusEnum.

setFrozen(address,uint8).notice: setFrozen sets the frozen status of an account to any of the values documented in                   FreezeStatusEnum.

setFundingClampPct(uint256,uint256).notice: setFundingClampPct sets the magnitude percentage that the funding rate clamps to if it                            is exceeded. This applies to both negative funding rate percentage                            or positive funding rate percentage.                            For example if this is set to a value corresponding to 4%, then                            funding rates of 5% and -6% would be clamped to 4% and -4%,                            respectively.

setFundingSum(uint256,int256,uint32,bool.notice: setFundingSum sets the funding sum for the specified perpetual contract. See dev                       comments below for applicable conditions.

setIgnOracle(uint256,bool).notice: CAREFUL: Configures the perpetual contract to ignore Oracle checks for:                    1. Setting the Index price.                    2. Setting the Funding rate (an Index price is provided for this and                    ordinarily checked against the Oracle price).                    3. Unpausing the perpetual contract the first time (ordinarily this requires                       an oracle to be configured).                    4. Falling back to the Oracle price for settlement and position operations.                       - For instance increasing position settlement collects negative PNL as                         collateral for conservatism based on the Index price. If the Index                         price is stale, it falls back to the Oracle price ordinarily. This                         fallback will not happen when ignOracle is true.                       - This also applies to liquidation, auto-deleveraging, force-close and                         unwind operations.                   Attempting to update the Oracle price will be ignored with event emitted.

setIndexOracleMaxAge(uint256,uint256).notice: setIndexOracleMaxAge sets the maximum age in seconds that the oracle can be for                              comparison purposes before comparisons to the oracle price value                              will fail.

setIndexOracleTolPer100k(uint256,uint256.notice: setIndexOracleTolPer100k sets the tolerance that the index price is permitted to                                  deviate from the stored oracle price value.

setInitialMarginFraction(uint256,uint256.notice: setInitialMarginFraction sets the Initial Margin Fraction (IMF), synonymous with the                                  maximum initial leverage of a position, for the specified                                  perpetual contract.

setLinkDsVerifier(address).notice: Sets the Chainlink Datastreams Verifier Proxy address for the entire exchange.

setLiquidationParams(uint256,uint256,uin.notice: setLiquidationParams sets the split for the proceeds of a liquidation, directing                              configurable portions of the funds to the insurance fund, the                              original position holder and to the protocol (liquidator).

setMaintenanceMarginFraction(uint256,uin.notice: setMaintenanceMarginFraction sets the Maintenance Margin Fraction (MMF). This is the                                      used to calculate the margin (value) that a position must                                      maintain in order to avoid liquidation by the system.

setMakerFee(uint256,uint256).notice: setMakerFee sets the maker fee, the fee applicable to orders that have posted to the                     book and are then matched to open a position.                     IMPORTANT: The maker fee only applies when opening a position--either a new                     position or increasing an existing position. It does NOT apply to reducing                     a position.

setMaxOpenInterest(uint256,uint256).notice: setMaxOpenInterest CAREFUL! This sets the maximum open interest of the perpetual                            contract. The effect is not a hard cap but rather determines the                            maximum initial leverage of a position, which can range from                            [1/100, 100.0], depending on the perpetual contract's initial                            setting and how far open interest has progressed towards the maximum                            value speicified here (and the unity and over collateral descent                            thresholds).                            See CalculationsLib::getCurrentIMF for more information.

setMinAccountOpenAmount(uint256).notice: setMinAccountOpenAmount sets the minimum amount that must be transferred into an                                 account when it is created. Transferring less than the minimum                                 amount will result in the account creation operation reverting.

setMinPost(uint256).notice: setMinPost sets the minimum amount for an order to post to the book. See dev notes                    below about behavior of this function for different order and position                    combinations.

setMinSettle(uint256).notice: setMinSettle sets the minimum amount for an order to settle on the book. See dev notes                      below about behavior of this function for different order and position                      combinations.

setOverCollatDescentThreshold(uint256,ui.notice: setOverCollatDescentThreshold CAREFUL! This sets the threshold at which the Initial                                       Margin Fraction (IMF) of the perpetual contract begins                                       its descent to the over collateral minimum IMF, 1/100th.                                       The threshold applies to the perpetual's open interest as                                       a fraction of the perpetual's maximum open interest.                                       See CalculationsLib::getCurrentIMF for more information.

setPermissionedCancelParams(uint256,uint.notice: setPermissionedCancelParams sets the parameters that determine if permissioned                                     cancellation criteria are applicable, allowing                                     adminCancelOrders to be applied to orders distant from the                                     mid-price that might performing denial of service attacks                                     on the order book. See documentation of the following                                     functions for more information:                                       * Admin::adminCancelOrders                                       * OrderBookLib::meetsOrderBookCapacityCancelCriteria

setPerpLinkDsFeedId(uint256,bytes32).notice: Configures a perpetual contract's Chainlink Datastream feed id. Requires that the         perpetual contract is paused and that the Chainlink Datastream Verifier Proxy has been         set. Reverts otherwise.

setPriceAdministrator(address,bool).notice: setPriceAdministrator CAREFUL! This function allows an address to be permitted to the                               role of price administrator. A price administrator can do                               important, financially impactful updates to a perpetual contract                               including setting the index price and funding rate for the                               perpetual contract.                               This role is not suitable for a multi-sig because the frequency                               of operations and number of operations is too high. Protection                               against this role being co-opted comes in the form of the price                               oracle gaurding price changes to be within a certain tolerance                               and age as well as a last resort, the owner called halt function                               which blocks addresses with this role from acting on the                               exchange.                               The number of price administrators is not limited as this role                               will likely operate with both failover and geographic redundancy.

setRecycleFee(uint256).notice: setRecycleFee sets the order recyling fee, which applies to all orders exchange wide.                       The recyling fee is remitted by an account posting an order to a                       perpetual's order book, which is then refunded when the order fills or is                       cancelled.                       Exceptions to the refunding include:                         a. When an order is expired.                         b. When an order cannot be filled due to failed risk analysis                            (collateralization).                         c. When an order meets certain permissioned cancellation criteria. (See                            documentation for Admin::adminCancelOrders).                       In these cases, the recyling fee is remitted to the order taker or                       administrator role (when the administrator role is order forwarding or                       performing permissioned adminCancelOrders calls).

setTakerFee(uint256,uint256).notice: setTakerFee sets the taker fee, the fee applicable to orders that execute immediately,                     matching positions on the order book, to open a position.                     IMPORTANT: The taker fee only applies when opening a position--either a new                     position or increasing an existing position. It does NOT apply to reducing                     a position.

setThousandthsTvlWRLS(uint256).notice: setThousandthsTvlWRLS sets the thousandths of Total Value Locked (TVL) in the protocol                               that can be withdrawn per withdraw rate limit period in the                               Withdrawal Rate Limit System (WRLS).                               The withdraw rate limit period is block based and is                               approximately an hour if Monad block consensus is averaging 0.42                               seconds.

setUnityDescentThreshold(uint256,uint256.notice: setUnityDescentThreshold CAREFUL! This sets the threshold at which the Initial Margin                                  Fraction (IMF) of the perpetual contract begins its descent to                                  unity. The threshold applies to the perpetual's open interest                                  as a fraction of the perpetual's maximum open interest.                                  See CalculationsLib::getCurrentIMF for more information.

unwindContract(uint256,uint256,bool).notice: Unwinds a paused perpetual contract for restart or delisting by paying out all         remaining positive valued positions from the perpetual contract's position and         insurance /balance. See dev note on the unwind process below.

updateIndexPricePNS(uint256,uint256).notice: updateIndexPricePNS updates the index price of the specified perpetual contract. See                             dev comments below for applicable conditions.

updateOraclePrice(uint256,bytes).notice: Attempts to update the specified perpetual contract's oracle price with a signed,         unverified, Chainlink Datastreams V3 price report.         IMPORTANT: This will emit OracleDisabled event and exit if the perpetual is configured                    to ignore oracle prices (see Perpetual::ignOracle and                    Owner::setIgnOracle).

withdrawCollateral(uint256).notice: withdrawCollateral allows an existing exchange account, determined by the address in                            msg.sender, to withdraw a specified amount of collateral tokens from                            their available collateral.

withdrawFromProtocol(uint256).notice: withdrawFromProtocol allows the owner account to withdraw collateral tokens from the                              protocol balance to an external wallet.

xferAcctToProtocol(uint256).notice: xferAcctToProtocol transfers funds from the user account, if it exists, corresponding                            to the address in msg.sender, to the protocol balance.

xferPerpInsToProtocol(uint256,uint256).notice: xferPerpInsToProtocol transfers funds from a specified perpetual contract's insurance                               fund balance to the protocol balance.

xferProtocolToAcct(uint256,uint256).notice: xferProtocolToPerp transfers funds from the protocol balance to a specified account's                            collateral balance.

xferProtocolToPerp(uint256,uint256,bool).notice: xferProtocolToPerp transfers funds from the protocol balance to a specified perpetual                            contract's position balance or insurance balance.

xferProtocolToRecycleBal(uint256).notice: xferProtocolToPerp transfers funds from the protocol balance to the protocol wide order                            recycling fee balance.
